The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live from arsenic, among other things, opens up new opportunities for new forms of life on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists have discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is in their opinion a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"It needs to grow either phosphorus or arsenic."
“This makes it something very special, even though it’s almost a kind of ‘foreign’ way of life,” said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears on Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in California’s Mono Lake continues to grow even further when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“You wonder what else is possible,” said co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were disclosed gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that organisms can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements in other planetary systems, and that the 'standard elements', which we believe are absolutely vital, are not necessarily specified," explains Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the University of Milton.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
“This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another,” Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Because arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she assumed that microbes exposed to both may be able to replace one element with the other.
“The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to its chemical behavior similar to that of phosphorus.”
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other."
“But the difference is so great that arsenic works differently than phosphorus, it gets into our biochemical system, where it almost everything is smeared,” explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
While the microbe grows better in phosphorus, it can also survive in arsenic, showing that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, on which arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a lecturer in microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but so far there has been no working example.
Arsenic occurred more frequently in the early Earth years, she says, which is why science has assumed that early life forms have used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than in the early Earth age," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
