China Continues Its Targets to Reduce Greenhouse Gases
China’s representative stated at COP16 that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprint and it would maintain its offer to cut 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China expects to reduce its supply of greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, assures Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country would have made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said his country has invested $245 million over the past four years to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its objectives, but would work together with the international community on this issue.
He explained that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
In all aspects, progress has been made, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which includes the targets for reducing gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the authorities of the states with those of the central state and the municipalities had cooperated to achieve the objectives of energy saving, efficient use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he said, some multi-year plans have already been attacked or completed, both those funded by the Chinese government and those that received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the program for the effective use of energy, which was introduced in the last five years and had received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and from private hands.
There is also a provincial project on climate change, another on the exchange of traditional light bulbs by energy saving bulbs and another on mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, a scientific government adviser on climate change in the country, confirmed that China’s efforts are far greater than would be commonly thought.
He pointed out that the per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China are six tons per person, while in the United States there are 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to environmental pollution.
Similarly, unprecedented progress is being made in the field of energy use. Energy efficiency has increased by twenty percent over the last five years and another is expected to happen by 2020, he said.
