The U.S. changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Persons must present themselves at the consulate at the visa application services before speaking; costs are reduced waiting times in this way.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa will change in the United States Embassy and Consulates.
During the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves before their consultation at the consulate at the Visa Application Services (ASC), the initial letters in English.
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which will be checked by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain benefits for the aspirants, including:
The total costs for the processing of the visa decrease, because it is no longer necessary to pay the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is delivered separately.
The applicant shall only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for a visa with application (including a temporary worker visa) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who want to extend their visa only do not need to have a conversation at the consulate, they only need to imagine at the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
As biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the conversation at the consulate will stay there less time than before.
Those applying for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo are no longer required to pay the $26 service fee.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found at the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
