Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed to voluntary reduction plans that would reduce global FCKW emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, one would have to subtract 5 Gt from this balance in order to stabilize the climate rise by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white glowing bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice as much.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last between 6000 and 10,000 hours on average.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those that the manufacturer Philips has launched this week – this company, by the way, has participated in the UN study – have a lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-light bulb, which is expected to cause an increase in the level of savings.
In addition to the fact that these completely new light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
